{"/service/ndnp/au/batch_au_dean_ver01/data/sn85038485/00340583024/1921030401/0057.xml":{"full_text":"GADSDEN FACTORY\nSouthern Company Invades\nBirmingham and Other\nLarger Fields\u2014Produc\ntion to Be Increased\nGadsden, Marrh 3.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The\nSouthern Manufacturing company, now\nrunning nine hours a day and planning\non a 10-hour shift within a short time, j\nis another concern in the Gadsden dis\ntrict which sees a brightening of the\nbusiness outlook and a relaxation of\nthe tension of the past few months.\nThe local concern has recently se-\ncured some big orders, notably one for j\na school building at Powderly, where\nthey will furnish two or three carloads\nof doors, sashes and other equipments 1\nAnother carload of finished goods will\nleave for Jasper this week, and other\nshipments for points in and out of Hhe\nstate are being invoiced.\nTwo feeks ago they opened an of- I\nfice in Birmingham, which is under the\ndirection of H. L. Gwinn. and Is located\nat 314 Twenty-first street. There is\nconsiderable activity in the building\ntrades in and around Birmingham and\nsome big jobs are contemplated which\nthe local people' plan on securing fancy\norders.\nThe Birmingham* venture will be fol\nlowed by the establishment of offices\nin Atlanta, and with those two central 1\noffices they expect to cover the field\nin the south thoroughly. The outlook\nis particularly promising, according to\nthe officials of the' company, who are\nin close touch with the situation\nthroughout the south.\nAsks Special Session\nAnniston. March 3.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Gov\nernor Kilby has been asked to call a j\nspecial session of the legislature for\nthe purpose of re-submitting the road\namendment question to the people of\nAlabama. The action was taken >ji\nWednesday afternoon at the reguiar\nTie at in g of the lo-ai civic body.\nMIC BUREAU\nSAVES $443,801\nShippers\u2019 Organization Has\nHandled So Far 102,869\nExpense \u2018Bills\nSince its organization, April 1, 1917, the\nBirmingham Traffic bureau has saved\nits merchant and manufacturer members\n(443,801 in hard cash.\nBut for the organization this money\nwould have been lost, the greater por\ntion of it at least, say the officials.\nIn the three and three-quarter years of\nits existence the total savings to mem\nbers were as follows:\nClaims paid, (340,932.\nChecking expense bills, (102,869.\nTotal, *4-13.801.\nThe bureau was organized by M. B.\nNorthingtcn, E. Wilkerson, Samuel L*.\nEarle, Murray Brown, W. D. Nesbitt and\na few other shippers. They looked over j\nthe country for the best traffic manager\nto be \u00a3ad and centered on O. JL. Bunn,\nthen manager of the Chattanooga Manu\nfacturers\u2019 association. Mr. Bunn haa\nbeen manager here since^\nThe annual meeting will be held at an\nearly date. Manager Bunn is preparing\nhis report.\nBank clearings for the first two\nmonths of the year show\u2019 a decrease of\n14 per cent under those of 1920, but an\nincrease of 39 per cent over those of\nTotal for this year and 1920 were as\nollows:\nJanuary\u2014(76,291,524 compared with (88,\n76,781.\nFebruary\u2014(60.716.9t)2 compared with $72,\n57,004.\nDecreases for this year\u2014(23,825,299.\nTotal for January id \u00abura*ry. 1919.\nvere (54.752,240, and (46,607.602, a total ot\njOI. 059,361.\nIncreased for this year compared with\n9 9. (36.941MW5. or 39 per cent.\nDecrease in clearings this year com\n>ared with 1920 is admitted to be partial\ndue to slowing down of various lines\n,f industrial enterprises, but it is also\nrrediteu to the bigger purenasing power\nif the 1921 dollar.\nFinancial and industrial leaders ex\npress themselves as surprised that clear\nngs have held up so well and point to\nhre inedease over the record if 1919 as\niliowing the continous growth and ex\npansion of the district:\nDINNER ENJOYED BY\nBLACH\u2019S SALESMEN\nMember* of the clothing' department\nat Klach's last night at a dinner at the\nHillman hotel, in a private dining room.\nAbout thirty clothing salesman and tail\nors attended. The dinner started at 6:30\no'clock.\nAfter the dinner, the possibilities o'\nthe spring trade were discussed. The\natfa'r which was greatly enjoyed bruit'\nup about 0 o'clock.\nCommittee to Meet\nTuscaloosa, Mar. D.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The ex\necutive committee of the State I\u2019niver\nHity will hold a meeting in this city Sat\nurday. The members ot the executive\ncommittee of the board of trustees are\nJudge Henry B. Foster, of Tuscaloosa.\nDaniel Pratt, of Prattville, I-Iill Fergu\nson. of Birmingham.\nJACOBS' PHARMACY\nCO.\nin a Few Days\nYou will be able to buy at\nBarker Bakery\nThe old-fashioned \u201cStollen\u201d Coffee\nCake, filled with tasty Qitron, lemon\npeel, eggs and milk\u2014emphasizing\nOld Time Quality\nAND HIGH CLASS SERVICE\nAt the Old Time Price\nWatch the Papers fot Announcement of the\nOpening Date\nBarker System of Bakeries\n1919 Third Ave.\nUnder Personal Supervision of Mr. Edward\nP. Vieh\nBefore Meals\nTWO SPOONFULS bf JACOBS\u2019\nLIVER SALT in a glue of hot\nwater before breakfast, keeps the\nliver and kidneys active end the aystem\nclear\u2014moke# you foal fit for o tool\ndogs\u2019' work.\nAt your drusrist's ssnsroua\nbottles, 35c an4 75c\nATLANTA, GA.\n(1)\nEffervescent Sait\nTRADE CONGRESS\nExtension of Work of Shipping\nBoard Vessels One\nof Planks\nBy Associated Prws\nWashington. March 3.\u2014Extension of\nthe work of the shipping board vessels\nwas urged in a platform adopted today\nby the Southern Commercial Congress\nat the closing session of its three days\u2019\nconference here. New trade routes\nshould be .opened, it said, consuls\ntrained to obtain business for American\nvessels and government owned boats\nallocated to every port in this country.\nThe platform also placed the dele-*\ngates on record as having equalized\nrailroad rates between inland points\nand south Atlantic ports, as well as to\nnorth Atlantic ports.\nOther points outlined in the platform\ndeclared that:\nSteps should be taken to bring about\na sound system for the sale and dis\ntribution of farm products.\nEfforts should be made among pro\nducers to secure the best co-operation\nIn marketing their supplies.\nDirect dealing between farmers and\nconsumer should be encouraged as\nmuch as \"possible.\nRailroad rates should be investigated\nand efforts made to so fix charges\nthat they will ndt be a detriment to the\nfarmer.\nAn Investigation should be made to\nestablish a national chamber of agri\nculture with a view to aiding farmers\nto find markets and furthering other\ncauses of the farm produce.\nThe convention also went on record\nas favoring the^establishment of aux\niliary congress^ in. the 16 southern\nstates.\nResolution.favoring the improvement\nof state highways and the creation of\nnational system of highways were also\nadopted.\nThe delegates today attended the\npresentation to the war department by\nthe Southern General society of a por\ntrait of the late Surgeon General\nGorgas. The presentation was made\nby the past president of the southern\nsociety. C. J. Owens. Maj. Gen. M. W.\nIreland* accepted the portrait for the\nj war department.\nFourth Assistant Postmaster General\nBlakeslee addressed the congress this\nafternoon on the transportation system\nof the country, pointing out the faults\nof the present sysermof railroading. He\nfavored the consolidation of lines where\nit could be shown there would be a ma\nterial benefit to the shippers and the\nj public.\nAt its concluding session tonight the\nj congress re-elected Thomas R. Preston\nof Chattanooga. Tern*., as president.\nOther officers elected were Albert E.\nThate. High Point. N. C.. first vice pres\nident; J. O. McKinley. Wheeling. W. Va.,\nsecond vice president; Clarence J.\nOwens of Washington, director gen\neral, and Mrs. C. C. Calhoun. Washing\nton. president general of the womans\nauxiliary.\nRates Adverse to South\u2019s In\nterests Still Unsettled and\nFight to Continue\nPresent state of the Iron market and\nthe greatly increased cost of assemb\nling raw materials at blast furnaces\nof the district will be presented before\nthe Public Service commission or\nMarch 28, at which time that body will\nagain hear argument as to these rates.\nThe rates were given a flat instead\nof percentage increase under the Mc\nAdo\u00b0 ofder of June, 1S18. and the Inter\nstate Commerce commission has added\nall the subsequent percentage increases\napplying generally. The iron produ\ncers have shown that the flat rate in\ncrease made the increase on raw mate\nrial assemblage come higher than had\nthe percentage basis been applied as in\ntile case of other products. They show\nthat with the higher flat rat\u00a7 as a base\nthe subsequent percentage increases\nhave likewise militated against them\nhaving the high rate to begin with.\nBirmingham iron is meeting with ex\ntremely sharp competition in every\nsection of the country lyid Birming\nham furnace operators are forced to\ntbe v,ery bottom'rock in order to keep\nBirmingham iron in the competitive\nf.eld. This also will be presented to\nthe commission.\nPetition of the operators is that the\nrublic Service commission do not ae\ncept the increases specified by the In\nterstate Commerce commission, but al\nio\"; rates that will even up those on\n;a\" material and other products.\nFIREMEN AID IN\nDESTRUCTION OF STILL\nCity fireman proved yesterday after\nloon that their work could be both don\nitructive and destructive, when the'\nanswered a call to 128 Third avenue\nsouth, to put out a fire caused by\nstill m operation at that address\n\u201cS1\u201d* t0 U* city, .the firemei\nnotified Lie police department. Deiec\nlies. McGill, Hubbard, ldllis and Grain\nwere( ^Patched to the scene io\nf'h,Lr h feder?d prohibition agent\nb\u00b0 hud been asked to go along.\nModern equipment was found in tli\nnouse. a still of 200 gallons capacit\u2019\n.vith a furnace in one of the rooms o\nhe house. Nine barrels of mash wer\nnfl^tl!?1 w. If WerW \"ad>- to b* \u2122.i\ndLr, Th. 'df \u00b0yed by the fed*Ta\njfflcers. The plant was owned am\nofficerK^ b> ne6roe8\u2019 according to th\nThe federal agents and the ctiy detec\nresult \u201cin6 lhe\u00b0rklnS \u00b0n C'UeS Whlch Wil\nresult In the arrest of the operator\nspy* t\nVERBENA STUDENT IS\nCHOSEN PRESIDENT OF\nMONTEVALLO Y. W. C. A.\nMontvallo. March 3.-(SpeciaI.)-Miss\nEvelyn Scott, Verbena, was chosen pres\nident of the Young Woman-* Christian\nassociation at Alabama Technical insti\ntute and College for Women, Montevalio,\nat the \u2022annual election of officers\nWednesday night. Miss Annie Laurie\nRc.bertaon, Clayton, was elected vice\npresident; Miss Edith Averyt. Colum\nbiana, secretary; Mias Willie Grace Stew\nart Daphne, treasurer.\nFor the first part of the Remaining\nterm of this school year these officers\nwill serve under the supervision of the\noutgoing officers, assuming the full re\nsponsibility of office before the close of\nthe school year. The officers whom\nI these girls will succeed are; Misses Bara\nFarris. Elba, president; Annie Carmich\nael. Hollins, vice president; Nena Mc\nDuffie, Attalla, recording secretary;\n\u2019.Louise Hinton, Prattville, corresponding\nsecretary; Anna Mae Allison. Townlcy.\ntreasurer.\nEnterprising Citizens Are Re\nlieving Famine By Starting\na Building Boom\nGadsden, March 3\u2014(Special.')\u2014Gads\nden is enjoying the spectacle of home\nbuilding* now in progress here, which\nbrings back memories of times in the\npast when homes wc.e not wo scarce\nas at present.\nTom Newberry is building several\nhomes on his property in the north part\nof the city, and in tlie* west section Mr.\nStocks has laid the foundation for two\nnew homes. About 25 houses are in\nprocess of construction tyere at the\npresent*time and more will be added to\nthe list within a few days, it is as\nserted.\nAmong the bigger projects looms the\nsection of a new business block on\nBroad street by'Mr. Rosenbaum, who\nwill soon give up his present quarters\nto the holesale Drug \u2022company.\nSELMA ELKS ELECT\nLODGE TO PROCURE\nLARGER CLUB ROOMS\nSelma, March 3.\u2014(Special.)\u2014Chambliss\nKeith was elected exalted ruler of the\nlocal order, B. P. O. E.. at the meeting\nheld (a*t evening at the Elk\u2019s club room*\non Washington street, at which were\npresent a number of enthusiastic mem\nbers.* Mr. Keith was also chosen delegate\nto the grand lodge meeting at Eos An\ngeles, to be held in July. The alternate\ndelegate is C. F. Brislin. 1\nOther officers elected were: C. L. l>e\nBardeleben, esteemed leading knight; O.\nM. Tate, eUeerr^fd loyal knight: C\\ K\nBrislin, esteemed lecturing knight; J. G.\nNorris, tyler; H. 1. Shelley, treasurer;\nRobert Coleman, secretary; T. A. Ale\nCask ill. trustee.\nDiscussion of new quarters for the\nElks* club was reopened, and plans dis\ncussed at length. Arrangements will\nsoon be made, it is thought, for provid\ning more commodious club rooms, made\nnecessary by the steadily growing mem\nbership.\nPlant ('loses Down\nGadsden. March 3.\u2014(Special.)\u2014The Gulf\nStates Steel company closed its plant un\nder orders received today for a period\nof 30 days. Lack of business was given\nas the reason for the action. Orders will\nbe filled from stock, it was announced.\nAdvertising and news\nitems, Cora Chapman\nBoterweg, 1912 Ave.\nE-. Russell Bros. Stu\ndio. Phone Easley 100\nENSLEY\nFor subscriptions, D.\nE. McCIInton, rrpre\nsents 11 v\u00ab. Phono Eas\nier 898.\nThe Age-Herald maintains special representatives in Ensley for handling\ncorrespondence, advertising and subscriptions.\nMiss Kirdie Syx, aged 19. passed* away i\nyesterday afternoon at 4:30 o'clock at!\nthe family residence in Fairfield. Ku- i\nneral arrangements will be announced i\nlater. The (ieceased is survived by her j\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. W. J. Syx; two:\nbrothers. Edward and Wilbur, and three j\nsisters. Gladys, Edith and Ruby Jerome.\nMOTHERS7 CLUB\nThe Twentieith Century Mothers' club\nmet Wednesday afternoon at the home\nof Mrs. G. N. Hamilton, with Mrs. J. S. j\nHamilton as joint hostess.\nAn election of officers was held with j\nthe following result: President. Mrs.\nG. W. Hamilton: vice president. Mrs. B.\nA. Brooks; secretary. Mrs. Frank L*e-\nmont; treasurer, Mrs. Sam Daffrorf;\nchairman of the programme committee, i\nMrs. C. I>. Gaines.\nMrs. Dominick \\Vas leader for the\nday and a short programme was given.\nthe topic being\u2019\"Sex Hygiene.\u201d\nThe living room was fragrant with\nhyacinths ami jonquils enhancing its j\nattractiveness.\nFollowing the programme the club j\nadjourned to the dining room, where a\nsalad course was served from an at\ntractive table, centered with spring\nflowers. Mrs. T*. t*. Whittle was the\nguest of the club.\nBIBLE CjfiASS ENTERTAINS\nThe Jackson Berean Bible class ot i\nthe Pike Avenue Baptist church will\nentertain Friday evening at 8 o\u2019clock\nthe Pike Avenue Baptist church. An\ninvitation is extended to the Bible\nj classes of the Ensley, Wylam. Pratt\nPity, Hunter Street,. North Birmingham\nand Twenty-seventh Street Baptist\nchurches. Ai^ interesting programme\nha-s been arranged, as follows:\nSelected music, orchestra. Invoca\ntion, Rev. S. W. Cliffe. Welcome ad\ndress. Rev. Theodore Harris. Violin\nsolo, 3|Ir. Cliff, with Miss Reid as ac\ncompanist. Four-minute reports from\neach class. Historian\u2019s report of the\nJackson Berean Bible class. Vocal se\nlection, ^labor\u2019s quartet. Reading, Miss*\nWeils. Violin solo. Mr. Cliff, with Miss\nCliff us accompanist. Music, Pratt City\norchestra. Reading. Miss Wells. Dia\nlogue, \"Seven Girls.\u201d Recitation, little\nMiss Irene Cross.\nFollowing the programme refresh\nments will be served and a social hour\nenjoyed.\nPLAY TO REPRESENTED\n\"The New Minister.\" a popular mu\nsical comedy from which scores were\nturned away for lack of room, when\npresented in West End last week, wll\u2019l\nbe staged at the Elks\u2019 hall in Ensley\nThursday evening. March 10, under the\nauspices of the Woman\u2019s auxiliary of\nI the First Presbyterian church of Ens\nj ley.\nThere are about 40 characters in the\n\u2018play and the members of the (Walker\nMemorial church, who are included in\nthe cast, are assisted by some of the\ntest talent in Birmingham. The play\nhas been pronounced by critics one of\nthe best ever staged In Birmingham by\nnonprofessionals. The musical num\nbers are new and pleasing.\nSHOWER PLANNED\nMrs. H. H. Spangler will give a cloth\ning shower Saturday morning from 10\nto 12 at her home at Shady Side, in\norder to equip the foundling recently\nadopted by Mr. and Mrs. T. P. Hous\nton.. Mrs. East, Mrs. J. F. Jackson and\nMrs. T. J. Matthews will be Joint hos\ntesses.\nThe foundling, a two weeks\u2019 old boy.\nwas left on the doorstep of Mr. and\nMrs. Houstor^ on Avenue, Saturday\nnight. No clue as to the identity of\nthe parents has been discovered. Mr.\nand Mrs. Houston have adopted the\nghild.\nMASONIC MEETING\nOfficers and members of the degree\nteam of Odenville lodge. No 706, A.\nF. A. M\u201e headed by J. S. Willbanks,\nworshipful master, attended the meet\ning of Ensley lodge No. 560 last night\nand conferred the third degree on a\ncandidate. The visitors proved very\nefficient and the degree was conferred\nin a most impressive manner.\nA feature of the meeting w'a\u00bb the\nrendition of a number of selection by a\nquartet of memDers or uaenvuie ioag\u00ab\nwhich w**f^ much enjoyed. Followinj\nthe work, a number of short tal\nwere made. The attendance was large\nand the affair proved of unusual in i\nterest.\nANNOUNCEMENTS\nAnnouncement is made that thoee d\u00ab\nsiring to procure tickets for the\ncal to be given at the Shady Side\nodist Episcopal church \u2018his evening\npurchase them at the Shady Side c\neery store.\nThe Chrysolite club will meet t\nafternoon with Mrs. A. G. Long, 1.\nTwenty-third street. Terrace Park\nEnsley Review, No. 14, Ladles of tl\nMaccabees, will met at the W. O. H\nhall on Avenue E this afternoon at\ni o\u2019clock.\nPRINTING\nA*\nPublishers of\nBooks, School Annuals, Catalogues a\nAlso\nPrinters, Raters, Binders\nLargeWorkOur Specialty\nBIRMINGHAM\nPrinting Company\nW. L Tries, Manager.\n1703 3d A to. Pkone M.\nInauguration!\nWarren G. Harding takes the oath today aa Pres\nident of the United States. He starts off doing\none of the big things in life.\nYou can yourself do one of the big things in life\ntoday\u2014open an account with this bank and start\nto save your money.\nUnexcelled Banking Facilities r\nCity National Bank\nof Bessemer\nFormerly The United State* Saving* Bank\nQFTlCERSi\nG. B. Hollingsworth. Cashiei^ W. W. Hollingsworth, Preside**\nVV. T. La them. Assistant Cashier J. C. B. Gwin. Vico President\n\u2014Jr\nMow Come The\nBi^er, Better\nGrapefruit\nThe big, juicy Sealdsweet grapefruit you can now buy\nare the very best from Florida\u2019s famous groves.\nFully a year ago these superior food-fruits were bom in th*\nfragrant blossoms of the grapefruit trees.\nIn the spring, during the summer, through the-fall and into the\nwinter they have been storing up Florida sunshine for your\nenjoyment.\nAs Sealdsweet grapefruit increase in size they gain in juice,\nflavor, sweetness and other elements that make them so de\nlightful when fully ripened.\nNow and for the next three or four months, your dealer can\nsupply you with the bigger, better Sealdsweet grapefruit that\ntune the meal and tone the system.\nTell your fruit man you want the large sizes of Sealdsweet\ngrapefruit, because they are fully matured and juicier than\npmaller ones\u2014he will furnish them if you insist.\n1\nmffismgit Oranges\nLike grapefruit, Sealdsweet oranges attain perfection at this\nseason, when fully tree-ripened.\nContaining more juice than oranges grown elsewhere, Fit\nSealdsweet oranges are now sweet and full-flavored to\nhighest degree. Ask your dealer for them.\nHandsome Book As a Gift\n\"Florida\u2019s Food-Fruits\u201d, beautifully Illustrated, contains directions for the\nuse of Sealdsweet grapefruit and oranges In a multitude of ways. Bend\nyour name and address for gift copy.\nFLORIDA CITRUS EXCHANGE\n633 Citizens Bank Building\nTampa, Florida\nTo make ran of dependable grapefruit and oranges look on boxes and\nwrappers for the Sesldsweet trademsrk of the Florida Citrus Buhaige, a\narrest body of Are thousand grore owners who pell their own fruits to avoid\nspeculation la them.\n3\n111\u00bb\nI <11","height":"28004","width":"19896"}}
